scenes.label: *from_AC_03_03b
texts: I went and contacted Oz again.
We connected to the plane's wi-fi and got a look inside while my buddy was checking out the STS...
I looked at Cross, who instantly joined the conversation.
Nice to meet you, Oz. I hear you've been helping this guy out.
You the one who looked into the STS? What's the status?
It's being hacked from the outside. The culprit is controlling 302's autopilot from outside the airport.
I guess that's who cut the airband too.
The plane's wi-fi still works, but it's unusable since so many people are trying to access it.
Hey, are there any other channels? Like, some emergency band that can only be used by the MTIL?
If they had one, they would've used it already.
You think you could take back the STS?
Definitely not in the time we have left...and even without the ticking clock, I'm not sure it'd be possible.
Can the STS be cut off? The hack would stop without it, wouldn't it?
Even the MTIL's manuals recommend disconnecting from the STS in an emergency. But if that worked here, we wouldn't need hackers, would we?
So that solution would be too easy...
Easy fixes probably lead to traps.
But the MTIL's thinking of disconnecting, right?
Yeah. That's why I warned 'em. Got 'em to postpone the disconnection. That idea came from the Cyber Countermeasures Office, though.
That's where the Cyber Force Dolls work, right?
They had weird outfits, but they were pretty good.
If we find the source of the guidance data, we might be able to overwrite it, and help 302 land.
With all the channels dead, that seemed like the obvious thing to do. The other hackers must've been trying the same thing.
But would the obvious course of action really solve a quest? If it was that simple, people would've completed one of the others.
I had to change my perspective and think outside the box.
What would you normally never do in this situation?
I could tell from her expression that she really didn't expect me to come back with another question.
Her expression turned quickly from shocked to serious, though.
Since everyone's trying to find a solution using the means already available to them, starting from scratch...
Momo's input helped me think outside the box.
She had a point. Everyone was too focused on existing methods. I mean, we were short on time, so I couldn't really blame them.
But that's exactly why I had to throw all those methods aside, and restart with a blank canvas.
What else can we throw into the mix?
Oz! You can get the captain's BMI password from the MTIL, right?
Kid, were you even listenin'? All the channels are dead. Even if we knew the password, we couldn't use it.
That's why we're gonna make a new channel.
Now's not the time for jokes. Even low-flyin' planes go at like 500km/h. Tryin' to approach one would be absolutely insane.
We'll use our new channel to connect to the captain's BMI and cancel the autopilot.
Puttin' in the code just shows an error. You know that, don't ya? You heard that airband recordin' too.
That's 'cause all the captain's doing is typing in the code from his BMI.
I'm not gonna be doin' that. I'm gonna use his authority to hack into the plane's systems.
You're actually gonna go with this insane plan?
This ain't a discussion. You in or not?
...Get back to me when the new channel's ready.

scenes.label: *dummy1
texts: Well, he did say to get back to him, so he must've been down with my plan, right?
I wasn't totally confident about that, though. Actually, I was getting kinda worried.
Man, this wasn't the time for his vague bullshit. He could've just said yes or no. Adults are such a pain in the ass.

scenes.label: *select1
texts: ...Yeah, the conversation left me kinda worried.
If I'm gonna Load, I'm gonna go all the way to the MTIL and get the password there.

scenes.label: *flag_on
texts: Whatever. I'll just assume we have a deal.
